mtk: mt_wifi: guard SAE cleanup in AP-only builds

The 7.6.7.3 AP source calls an SAE helper even when DOT11_SAE_SUPPORT is
disabled, while SAE_CFG is only present when SAE support is compiled.  Its
interface close path also declares pAd only for combined AP+STA builds even
though the AP-only body always uses it.  The AP ioctl, MBSS, WDS and STA ioctl
implementations also comment out the central driver header despite directly
using RTMP adapter, channel, wifi_dev and debug declarations.  The station
sync path likewise validates an SAE-only BSS field when SAE is disabled.
Finally, its authentication flood check leaves an else-closing brace and an
802.11r field access active when SAE and FT are disabled.  Its radiotap path
also calls netif_rx_ni(), which was removed from current kernels.  MT7986 then
includes a per-PA EEPROM header which this release never generates; its bin2h
tool instead writes the selected image to the generic mt7986_e2p.h already
included immediately above.  Keep these paths consistent with the selected
feature guards, include the complete driver declarations, use the context-safe
netif_rx() replacement, drop the unused missing EEPROM include, and only
register MT7986 WLAN-service debug callbacks when their implementations are
compiled.  The ATE channel switch path also used the WLAN-service-only
GET_MAX_PATH helper, so access the same core chip capability directly when the
service layer is disabled.  Finally, the peer measurement request handler
compiled its active/passive scan branch without OFFCHANNEL_SCAN_FEATURE even
though the branch references state and helpers provided only by that feature.
Keep Beacon Table mode available and report other modes as incapable when the
off-channel scanner is absent.  The non-service ATE path also used an adapter
name which does not exist in its RU error handling and omitted the band index
from one TX-vector check; use the function's adapter and the complete callback
signature.  The legacy HQA ioctl path likewise leaked WLAN-service-only band,
logging, and status symbols into a non-service build; use the native testmode
band count, driver logger, and invalid-data status there.  The native ATE
implementation has the same layering leak: it uses the service-only antenna
path helper, pre-calibration operation enums, and integer typedef.  Read the
core path table directly and provide native enum/type equivalents when the
service layer is absent.

